Dear Governor Perdue,

Would you be interested in saving a 1/4 million ($$)dollars or even more.

A recent renovation of the Governors mansion was required because it had acquired massive amounts of black mold.  This was truly detrimental to those living, working, visiting, and doing business there.  Although age was blamed for some of the renovations it was poor housecleaning habits that contributed to most of the black mold.  Using this as an example, these problems are occurring in many of our state buildings.  It is becoming more unhealthy for the people working there and I can only predict that in the near future there may be lawsuits from people who are being exposed to many health hazards. 

What it boils down to is that the janitorial contracts being issued by the state are managed by many different organizations.  They all have different contracts.  They all have different standards.  The quality of their inspections vary widely.  The demands of the contracts are anywhere from 1 page to 40 pages.  How can there be such a diversity of service? 

The Department of Administration has some of the large buildings in Raleigh, they have 6 Inspectors for 8 buildings and there are many complaints about their service.  The DOT Support Services have 5 large buildings in Raleigh and have 92 other DMV and DOH contracts across the State, they only have 2 Inspectors.  The DOH manages many of their own building and coordination is done locally.  Plus, there are many, many, independent state buildings who manage their own contracts and enforcement of the contracts are poor.  Many of our leased building are cleaned by the owners of the buildings and have no established standards of cleaning set by the state.


My proposal is to put all of the cleaning contracts under one organization.  There are plenty of advantages in doing this:


1.  Contract costs can be reduced by regionalizing the contracts and making group bids.


2.  Inspections can be balanced, documented, and done more often.


3.  A higher level of cleaning can be achieved.


4.  Some personnel can be eliminated.


5.  Bidding of multiple contracts can be done competitively, thus reducing overall costs.


6.  Single contract bids can be eliminated.


7.  Poor service can be detected quicker and fixed appropriately.


8.  Bids can be awarded to the lowest responsible bidder.



I'm sure that more advantages can be found if this is thoroughly investigated.  Each one of items mentioned above are there because I have seen these problems and I also see solutions.  Please give me the opportunity to present these issues, explain the problems, and propose solutions.  My work history has give me the knowledge and experience to streamline this project.  I was employed with IBM for 28 years as their Sr. Security Consultant, have been a Diebold employee for 5 years as the Manager of a 12 Million dollar budget, and as a Facilities Inspector for 6 years with the DOT it has given me the time, knowledge, and experience to reorganize the cleaning contracts of the State.  Please give me the opportunity to present this information to you.



Dennis Beck

Facilities Inspector (Statewide)




